Another great asset possessed by Lucretius is the imaginative insight and exuberant originality with which he pictures to himself and unfolds to his readers the long periods of the early struggles of primitive man in the dim recesses of the past, until gradually, by the processes of evolution, they reached that development of civilization which culminated in the civilization of the poet's own day (‘ ad summum donec venere cacumen ²).
